.\" Man page for origin
.\" Origin Protocol — cryptographic provenance for digital artifacts
.\"
.TH ORIGIN 1 "2026-06-10" "1.2.0" "Origin Manual"
.SH NAME
origin \- cryptographic provenance for digital artifacts
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B origin
\fIcommand\fR [\fIoptions\fR] [\fIargs\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Origin is the smallest possible protocol for cryptographically verifiable
digital provenance. It binds an artifact hash, a public key, and a timestamp
into a self-contained signed statement. Anyone can verify \(em offline,
instantly, with no dependencies.
.P
The statement is a 6- or 7-line UTF-8 text file (the \fI.origin\fR file)
containing the artifact hash, timestamp, public key, and Ed25519 signature.
The canonical body (what is signed) excludes the timestamp and signature.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B hash \fIpath\fR
Compute the SHA-256 hash of a file.
Prints \fIsha256:<hex>\fR to stdout.
.TP
.B keygen [\fB--output\fR \fIdir\fR]
Generate an Ed25519 key pair.
Writes \fIorigin-secret.key\fR and \fIorigin-public.key\fR to the
specified directory (default: current directory).
Public key is printed to stdout.
Secret key file permissions are set to 0600 on Unix.
.TP
.B sign \fIpath\fR \fB--key\fR \fIfile\fR [\fB--time\fR \fIts\fR] [\fB--parent\fR \fIpath\fR]
Sign an artifact, producing a \fI.origin\fR statement file.
.br
Secret key sources (in priority order):
.br
1. \fB$ORIGIN_KEY\fR environment variable
.br
2. \fB--key\fR \fIfile\fR
.br
3. \fB--key\fR \fI-\fR (read from stdin)
.TP
.B verify \fIstatement\fR \fIartifact\fR [\fB--trusted-key\fR \fIfile\fR] [\fB--consistency-only\fR] [\fB--parent\fR \fIparent_stmt\fR \fIparent_art\fR]
Verify a provenance statement against an artifact.
With \fB--trusted-key\fR, pins verification to a specific public key.
With \fB--consistency-only\fR, checks hash + signature without key pinning.
With \fB--parent\fR, also verifies the parent in a provenance chain.
Returns VERIFIED or FAILED. Exit code 0 on success, 1 on failure.
.TP
.B audit \fIstatement\fR
Display a human-readable audit of a statement.
Does NOT perform cryptographic verification.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Print help information.
.TP
.B \-V, \-\-version
Print version information.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Generate a key pair
origin keygen
.TP
Sign a file
origin sign release.tar.gz \-\-key origin\-secret.key
.TP
Verify a signed file (with trusted key)
origin verify release.tar.gz.origin release.tar.gz --trusted-key origin-public.key
.TP
Verify a signed file (consistency only, no key pinning)
origin verify release.tar.gz.origin release.tar.gz --consistency-only
.TP
Chain a new statement to a parent
origin sign v2.0.tar.gz \-\-key origin\-secret.key \-\-parent v1.0.tar.gz.origin
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
0
Successful verification.
.TP
1
Verification failure or error.
.SH SECURITY
The verifier must obtain the trusted public key through an external
channel (website, Signal, Keybase, etc.). The protocol does not
distribute or authenticate public keys.
.P
See RFC-0001.md, THREAT_MODEL.md, and TRUST_MODEL.md for the
full security analysis.
.SH SEE ALSO
